1. Lambda Expressions (Functional Interface) $\lambda$
ðŸ§  Logic:A Lambda Expression (or Lambda function) is a short block of code that takes parameters and returns a value. It provides a clear and concise way to represent an $\mathbf{Anonymous~Function}$ (a function without a name).Lambdas are primarily used to provide the implementation for a Functional Interface (an interface with exactly $\mathbf{one~abstract~method}$). This allows Java to adopt a functional programming style.ðŸ“Œ Example (Simplified Syntax):Java// Traditional way:
/*
(int a, int b) -> {
    return a + b;
}
*/

// Simplest form of Lambda:
// (parameters) -> expression_body

(a, b) -> a + b; // Takes two arguments and returns their sum.
ðŸ¤¹â€â™€ï¸ Java Code (Using Lambda with Runnable):Javapublic class LambdaDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // 1. Traditional Anonymous Inner Class (Verbose)
        Runnable r1 = new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                System.out.println("Thread 1 running.");
            }
        };

        // 2. Lambda Expression (Concise Implementation of Runnable's run() method)
        Runnable r2 = () -> {
            System.out.println("Thread 2 running.");
        };

        new Thread(r1).start();
        new Thread(r2).start();

        // 3. Simple Consumer example (Consumer is a Functional Interface)
        java.util.function.Consumer<String> printer = s -> System.out.println("Message: " + s);
        printer.accept("Hello Lambda");
    }
}
ðŸ§¾ Notebook Points:JavaðŸ“˜ Lambda Expressions:
â†’ Anonymous function used for concise code
â†’ Syntax: (parameters) -> body
â†’ Requirement: Used to implement Functional Interfaces (Single Abstract Method)
